Ticket ID: SEC-DEV-2025-09-LAPTOPII
Title: Security Audit, Hardening, and Firmware Integrity Verification — Laptop II
Classification: Cybersecurity / Endpoint Hardening / Preventive Security Audit
Status: Completed – Monitoring Phase
Priority: High
Affected Asset: Laptop II (Windows 11 endpoint)
Related Tickets: SYS-VAL-2026-02-AWX17R1-II, SEC-DEV-2025-10-LAPTOPII-CLEANOS, SEC-DEV-2025-10-LAPTOPII-AWCC

Executive Summary
Laptop II underwent a full cybersecurity audit and hardening procedure after observing identical Windows Update and DISM integrity anomalies previously identified on Desktop II. While the most probable root cause is a Windows communication or servicing stack inconsistency, the possibility of system-level compromise or firmware persistence was treated as a risk scenario.
A comprehensive remediation and validation process was performed, including:
	• Deep malware removal using TRON Script
	• Network hardening and port exposure reduction
	• Remote access and remote execution disabling
	• PowerShell and WinRM restriction
	• DNS hardening and network isolation configuration
	• Firmware and UEFI integrity verification using CHIPSEC
	• Optional firmware analysis preparation using Intel ME Analyzer
	• Windows servicing stack repair and system integrity validation
No confirmed indicators of compromise (IOC) were detected. System is currently considered secure and hardened.

Business Impact
Risk Level Before Remediation: Moderate
Risk Level After Remediation: Low
Potential risks addressed:
	• Unauthorized remote access
	• Firmware-level persistence threats
	• Remote PowerShell abuse
	• Windows servicing stack corruption persistence
	• Exposure to network-based lateral movement
Laptop II is now operating under hardened security posture with reduced attack surface.

Root Cause Analysis
Most likely cause:
	• Windows servicing stack communication bug triggered by:
		○ Identical Windows 11 version across devices
		○ Similar Windows Update servicing state
		○ Similar security hardening configurations
		○ Similar software environment
Less likely but mitigated scenarios:
	• Malware persistence
	• Remote PowerShell exploitation
	• Unauthorized remote services activation
	• Firmware-level tampering

Detailed Technical Actions Performed
Phase 1 — Malware Removal and System Sanitization
	• TRON Script executed as primary malware and persistence removal framework.
	• Performed malware removal, rootkit detection, registry cleanup, scheduled task and autoruns cleanup, Windows servicing stack repair, temporary file cleanup, Defender reset and repair.
	• Execution: tron.bat as Administrator, duration ~4–8 hours.
	• Result: No persistent malware detected; system integrity restored.

Phase 2 — Network Exposure and Port Hardening
	• Checked open ports (netstat -ano) and listening services (Get-NetTCPConnection -State Listen).
	• Closed/verified absence of high-risk ports: 135, 139, 445, 5985, 5986, 3389.
	• Firewall rules verified (wf.msc) to disable Remote Desktop, Remote Assistance, and File/Printer Sharing (external profiles).

Phase 3 — Remote Access and Remote Execution Hardening
	• Disabled Remote Desktop (SystemPropertiesRemote.exe).
	• Disabled WinRM: winrm quickconfig /disable, Stop-Service WinRM, Set-Service WinRM -StartupType Disabled.
	• Disabled PowerShell Remoting: Disable-PSRemoting -Force.

Phase 4 — Service and Remote Registry Hardening
	• Disabled Remote Registry: Stop-Service RemoteRegistry, Set-Service RemoteRegistry -StartupType Disabled.

Phase 5 — Network Adapter and DNS Hardening
	• Secured DNS configuration: 1.1.1.1, 1.0.0.1, alternative 8.8.8.8 / 8.8.4.4.
	• Disabled unnecessary bindings: File and Printer Sharing, Microsoft Network Adapter Multiplexor Protocol.

Phase 6 — Windows Integrity Verification
	• Executed sfc /scannow and DISM /Online /Cleanup-Image /RestoreHealth.
	• Result: Windows component store integrity restored.

Phase 7 — Firmware Integrity Validation
	• Installed Python (winget install Python.Python.3).
	• Downloaded CHIPSEC (git clone https://github.com/chipsec/chipsec.git → python setup.py install).
	• Executed firmware whitelist check: python chipsec_main.py -m tools.uefi.whitelist.
	• Result: No unauthorized firmware modifications detected.

Phase 8 — Intel Management Engine Verification Preparation
	• Downloaded ME Analyzer (https://github.com/platomav/MEAnalyzer) for optional advanced validation.

Phase 9 — Windows Security Verification
	• Verified Windows Defender status (Get-MpComputerStatus) and protections enabled: real-time, cloud, tamper.

Phase 10 — Startup and Persistence Verification
	• Checked startup entries (taskmgr → Startup), scheduled tasks (taskschd.msc), running processes (tasklist), autoruns (TRON validation).
	• Result: No suspicious persistence mechanisms found.

Final System State
	• Remote access, PowerShell, WinRM, Remote Registry disabled.
	• Network hardened, DNS secured, ports closed.
	• Firmware integrity validated, malware scans completed.
	• Windows servicing stack repaired.

Verification Commands Summary
	• Network: netstat -ano, Get-NetTCPConnection
	• Service: Get-Service WinRM, Get-Service RemoteRegistry
	• Defender: Get-MpComputerStatus
	• Integrity: sfc /scannow, DISM /Online /Cleanup-Image /RestoreHealth
	• Firmware: python chipsec_main.py -m tools.uefi.whitelist

Conclusion
	• No confirmed compromise, no firmware tampering, no malware persistence, no unauthorized remote access.
	• Most likely explanation: Windows servicing stack communication issues.
	• System is now considered secure, hardened, and operational.
